sols:
The solution of the differential equation $\frac{dT}{dt} = k(T-T_s)$
is\\\\ $\displaystyle T - T_s = (T_0 - T_s)e^{kt}$, where $T$ is the
temperature of an object, $T_s$ is the temperature of its surroundings,
and $k$ is some constant.

We are given that $T_s = 40,\, T_0 = 70,\, T(0.5) = 60$, where $t$ is in
hours. Thus we begin by solving for $k$:

\begin{align*}
T(t) - T_s &= (T_0 - T_s)e^{kt}
\\ 60 - 40 &= (70 - 40)e^{k\cdot0.5}
\\ e^{0.5k} &= \frac{2}{3}
\\ \frac{1}{2}k &= \ln\frac{2}{3}
\\ k &= \ln\frac{4}{9}
\\
\\ \therefore T(t) &= 30e^{\ln\left(\frac{4}{9}\right)\cdot t} + 40
\\ &= 30\left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^t + 40
\end{align*}

Finally, solving for $t$ when $\displaystyle T(t) = 50$ yields:

\begin{align*}
50 &= 30\left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^t + 40
\\ \frac{1}{3} &= \left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^t
\\ \ln\frac{1}{3} &= t\ln\frac{4}{9}
\\ t &= \frac{\ln\frac{1}{3}}{\ln\frac{4}{9}} = {\color{blue} \frac{\ln3}{\ln\frac{9}{4}} \,\,\mathrm{hours}}\end{align*}

hints:
\textbf{Newton's Law of Cooling} states that the \emph{rate of cooling}
of an object is proportional to the \emph{temperature difference}
between the object and its surroundings. (Try expressing this as a
differential equation.)
